snippet.textDisplay:
Looking at comments about it now, people are upset that AMD ist not going to be supporting the 300-Series boards because 'they are the same electronics and manufacturers should be doing it then'.
Like, seriously people? I feel like it's never enough and you forget more and more that Intel is not doing 1% of what AMD is trying to make reality now. I see why people are still upset, but if you really can and will buy a new CPU every few years then why can't you just upgrade your motherboard as well? Yes, it's a hundred bucks on top, but then you could maybe skip on the +10% power for one year, save that money and buy a Mainboard and CPU together in two years? 

So yes, would be nice if AMD did also bring support to 300-Series boards, but beggars can't be choosers - not defending AMD tho since obviously they have power to support some margin of backwards compatibility. Of course we have to complain if something is wrong or to our disliking but at one point I fail to see the difference between just wanting to complain and begging (what about Series 300... 200, etc.) Vs. Actually being a problem or hurtful lies by manufacturers. Yes, support for things needs to be longer (looking at you Android updates) but in this case it's physical limitations and not lazy manufacturers.
